This paper is likely to belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category as it discusses the design of a formal semantics for Rust, which is a programming language. It also mentions the type system and ownership, which are key features of programming languages. 

It could also belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category as it mentions the use of progress and preservation to prove type soundness, which are concepts from mathematical logic. 

The Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category is also likely as the paper discusses the design of a programming language and its type system, which are important aspects of software engineering. 

The Formal Languages and Automata Theory (cs.FL) sub-category is a possibility as the paper discusses a family of languages of increasing expressive power, which is a concept from formal language theory. 

Finally, the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category is a possibility as the paper mentions the RustBelt effort to verify the safety of unsafe code in Rust's standard library, which is related to security.
